OCP-AI MetalLB + CNPG Troubleshooting Walkthrough
March 31, 2026

Problem: MetalLB L2 VIP services on VLAN interfaces (bnd0.1794/1797/1798) not reachable cross-node or externally. 8 LoadBalancer services across dev/test/prod all timing out.

Troubleshooting approach: Start at L2 and work up. At each step, if it looks good, move to the next layer. If something's off, dig in there.


1. Verify MetalLB is assigning IPs and speakers are running

oc get svc -A --field-selector spec.type=LoadBalancer
oc get pods -n metallb-system
oc logs -n metallb-system -l component=speaker --tail=50

What I found: Speaker pods were all Running 2/2. Every service had an EXTERNAL-IP assigned. I didn't see ARP-specific messages in the speaker logs — turns out the FRR-based speakers in this version don't log gratuitous ARPs like older MetalLB did. So I moved on to checking ARP directly.

Note on speaker logs: Even after everything is fixed and traffic is flowing, the speaker logs still show "no route to host" errors for some ServiceL2Status objects in pai-test (l2-q9wzr, l2-gh5t9). Those are stale status objects that the speaker is trying to update — it gets "Value is immutable" back and retries. It's not a routing problem, it's a stuck Kubernetes status resource. Traffic is fine, the errors are cosmetic. Hasn't impacted anything.

Why check this first: Most common LB issue is MetalLB itself — wrong pool, speaker not running, L2Advertisement not matching. Eliminates the obvious stuff fast.


2. Check ARP — is the VIP reachable at Layer 2?

From inside the cluster (same VLAN):
oc debug node/ocp-ai-master01.calix.local -- chroot /host arping -c 3 -I bnd0.1794 10.172.194.160

What I found: arping returned 0 responses — both from my workstation and from inside the cluster. From the workstation that's expected (different subnet, ARP is Layer 2 only, doesn't cross VLANs). From inside the cluster on the same VLAN, 0 responses likely means the VIP is owned by the same node I'm arping from (master01 — can't arping yourself), or the FRR-based MetalLB speaker handles gratuitous ARP differently than older versions.

ARP didn't give me a clear answer, so I moved on to tagging the traffic to get definitive proof.


3. Tag the traffic at ingress

Why I did this: ARP didn't tell me if packets were reaching the node. So I tagged the traffic instead. If my tag fires, the packet is hitting the kernel. If it doesn't, it's a switch/VLAN/L2 problem and I'm looking in the wrong place.

How tagging works: iptables lets you insert a LOG rule at any stage of the kernel's packet path. Every time a matching packet passes through that stage, it writes a line to dmesg with whatever prefix you give it. The prefix is just a label — I used "RAW-PRE: " so I could grep dmesg and find my entries.

I put the tag at the earliest possible stage — the raw table in PREROUTING. PREROUTING is the first stop when a packet enters the node, before any routing decision.

Step 1 — tag the traffic:
oc debug node/ocp-ai-master01.calix.local -- chroot /host iptables -t raw -I PREROUTING -d 10.172.194.160 -j LOG --log-prefix "RAW-PRE: "

Step 2 — test from my workstation:
nc -zv 10.172.194.160 9000

Step 3 — check dmesg for the tag:
oc debug node/ocp-ai-master01.calix.local -- chroot /host dmesg | grep RAW-PRE | tail -5

What I saw: My RAW-PRE tag fired in dmesg every time I ran nc. I could see IN=bnd0.1794 and DST=10.172.194.160. Packets were definitely hitting the kernel. So the problem was somewhere after ingress — the packet arrives but something drops it before it reaches the pod.


4. Check if DNAT rules exist for the VIP

What is DNAT: Destination NAT — it rewrites the destination IP. When traffic hits the VIP (e.g. 10.172.194.160), DNAT changes it to the ClusterIP (172.30.x.x) so the kernel can forward it to the pod. Without DNAT, the node has no idea what to do with traffic destined for the VIP.

Why I checked this: I now know packets are reaching the node (step 3). Next question is — does the kernel know what to do with them? DNAT rules are what map VIPs to ClusterIPs. If those rules don't exist, the packet just sits there.

To see DNAT rules for a specific VIP:
oc debug node/ocp-ai-master01.calix.local -- chroot /host iptables-save -t nat | grep 10.172.194.160

To see all DNAT rules with packet counts:
oc debug node/ocp-ai-master01.calix.local -- chroot /host iptables -t nat -L OVN-KUBE-EXTERNALIP -nv

What I found: DNAT rules were there for every VIP. Here's what the chain looks like — each VIP maps to a ClusterIP:

  10.172.194.160:9000  → 172.30.168.89:9000   (MinIO dev)
  10.172.194.161:19530 → 172.30.156.22:19530  (Milvus dev)
  10.172.194.163:5432  → 172.30.23.200:5432   (PostgreSQL dev)
  10.172.198.160:9000  → 172.30.17.247:9000   (MinIO test)
  10.172.198.161:19530 → 172.30.154.19:19530  (Milvus test)
  10.172.202.160:9000  → 172.30.161.228:9000  (MinIO prod)
  10.172.202.161:19530 → 172.30.250.144:19530 (Milvus prod)
  10.172.202.163:5432  → 172.30.93.138:5432   (PostgreSQL prod)

DNAT rules were all there. The kernel knew about the VIPs. So the issue was what happened after DNAT rewrote the destination.


5. After DNAT — tag the traffic at the exit

Why I did this: Packets arrive (step 3), DNAT rules exist (step 4), but nc still times out. Something is happening between DNAT and the pod. On OVN-Kubernetes, DNAT'd traffic needs to enter OVN via br-ex. So I tagged the traffic again, but this time at POSTROUTING — the last stop before a packet leaves the node. By this point DNAT has already rewritten the destination and the kernel has made its routing decision. The tag here shows me the OUT= interface — which door the packet is actually leaving through.

Step 1 — tag the DNAT'd traffic at POSTROUTING:
oc debug node/ocp-ai-master01.calix.local -- chroot /host iptables -t nat -I POSTROUTING -m conntrack --ctstate DNAT -j LOG --log-prefix "POST-DNAT: "

Step 2 — test again from my workstation:
nc -zv 10.172.194.160 9000

Step 3 — check dmesg for the tag:
oc debug node/ocp-ai-master01.calix.local -- chroot /host dmesg | grep POST-DNAT | tail -5

What I saw: In dmesg I saw OUT=bnd0.1794. The DST had changed to 172.30.x.x (ClusterIP — so DNAT worked), but the packet was exiting through the VLAN interface instead of br-ex. That was the breakthrough — the kernel was routing the DNAT'd packet back out the VLAN gateway instead of into OVN.


6. OVN-Kubernetes network config changes — ipForwarding and routingViaHost

Why I did this: After seeing OUT=bnd0.1794 in step 5, my first thought was that OVN wasn't allowing traffic to be forwarded between interfaces. By default, OVN-Kubernetes sets ipForwarding to Restricted — it only forwards Kubernetes-originated traffic. If external traffic hits a VLAN interface and needs to cross into br-ex, the kernel might not forward it because OVN hasn't told it to.

What I changed:
oc patch network.operator cluster --type merge -p '{"spec":{"defaultNetwork":{"ovnKubernetesConfig":{"gatewayConfig":{"ipForwarding":"Global","routingViaHost":true}}}}}'

ipForwarding: Global — tells OVN-Kubernetes to allow IP forwarding across all managed interfaces (br-ex, VLAN interfaces, etc.), not just for Kubernetes traffic. Without this, the kernel can silently refuse to forward packets between interfaces that OVN manages.

routingViaHost: true — makes OVN route traffic through the host kernel's networking stack instead of through OVN's internal gateway. This is needed when traffic arrives on a secondary interface (like bnd0.1794) and needs to reach OVN — the host kernel has to handle the routing decision, not OVN's internal gateway.

How to verify the change took effect:
oc get network.operator cluster -o jsonpath='{.spec.defaultNetwork.ovnKubernetesConfig.gatewayConfig}' | jq .

What happened: Applied both changes. Tested again with nc -zv to the VIP — still timed out. The changes were necessary (traffic needs to be forwarded between interfaces) but they weren't enough on their own. The packet was still going out bnd0.1794 instead of br-ex. That told me the problem wasn't OVN blocking forwarding — it was the kernel's routing decision sending the packet to the wrong interface in the first place. So I dug into the policy routing tables.

Red Hat docs:
- https://access.redhat.com/solutions/7117243 — Symmetric Routing for MetalLB on secondary interfaces
- https://access.redhat.com/solutions/7053694 — routingViaHost with secondary interface for br-ex


7. Policy routing tables — the root cause

What are policy routing tables: NMState creates these (tables 100/101/102) for source-based routing on VLAN interfaces. They override the main routing table. If a packet's source IP is on a VLAN subnet, the kernel uses the policy table instead of the main table to decide where to send it.

What is br-ex: The OVN external bridge — the door into OVN networking. All DNAT'd traffic needs to exit through br-ex so OVN can route it to the right pod. 169.254.0.4 is the OVN gateway router sitting on the other side of br-ex.

Why I checked this: Step 5 showed OUT=bnd0.1794 and the OVN config changes in step 6 didn't fix it. The kernel was still sending the packet out the VLAN interface instead of br-ex. Linux policy routing (ip rule) can override the main routing table. Once I saw the wrong OUT= interface and knew it wasn't an OVN forwarding issue, the policy tables were the next thing to check.

Check the rules and tables:
oc debug node/ocp-ai-master01.calix.local -- chroot /host ip rule show
oc debug node/ocp-ai-master01.calix.local -- chroot /host ip route show table 100
oc debug node/ocp-ai-master01.calix.local -- chroot /host ip route show table 101
oc debug node/ocp-ai-master01.calix.local -- chroot /host ip route show table 102

What I found: The policy tables (100/101/102) only had a default gateway route via the VLAN interface and the local subnet route. No route to 172.30.0.0/16 (ClusterIP range). So here's what was happening: after DNAT changes the destination to a ClusterIP (172.30.x.x), the packet hits the policy table because the source IP is on the VLAN subnet. The table has no route for 172.30.0.0/16, so it falls through to the default route, which sends it out bnd0.1794 toward the VLAN gateway. That gateway has no idea what 172.30.x.x is, and the packet is gone.

Fix — add the ClusterIP route to each table:
ip route add 172.30.0.0/16 via 169.254.0.4 dev br-ex table 100
ip route add 172.30.0.0/16 via 169.254.0.4 dev br-ex table 101
ip route add 172.30.0.0/16 via 169.254.0.4 dev br-ex table 102

169.254.0.4 is the OVN gateway router on br-ex.

Verify with: ip route show table 101 — should now include 172.30.0.0/16 via 169.254.0.4 dev br-ex.

After adding the route to table 101, I tested from master02 to a VIP on master01 using curl. I got back an HTTP 403 Forbidden from MinIO. That 403 was actually a good sign — before the fix I got nothing (nc timeout, curl hang). The 403 meant the packet went all the way through DNAT, into OVN via br-ex, hit the MinIO pod, and MinIO responded. It denied access because I hit it without credentials, but the point is end-to-end connectivity was working. Timeout = packet dropped in the kernel. 403 = full round trip.

VLANs 1797 and 1798 were still broken after this — that turned out to be rp_filter (step 9).


8. MASQUERADE — needed for return traffic

What is MASQUERADE: It rewrites the source IP of the packet to the node's own IP. The kernel's connection tracking (conntrack) remembers the original source, so when the reply comes back, conntrack undoes the rewrite and sends it to the real client. Think of it as the node pretending the traffic came from itself.

Why it's needed here: Even with the route fix, DNAT'd packets arriving on br-ex still have my workstation's source IP (10.172.248.105). OVN only knows pod and service IPs — it has no route back to an external IP. MASQUERADE makes OVN think the traffic came from the node, so OVN sends the reply to the node, and conntrack maps it back to the real client.

iptables -t nat -I POSTROUTING -m conntrack --ctstate DNAT -o br-ex -j MASQUERADE

What I found: Without MASQUERADE, the packet entered OVN correctly (I could see OUT=br-ex in my tag) but I still got no response. After adding MASQUERADE, responses started coming back. The routing fix (step 7) got the packet into OVN, but the reply had nowhere to go. MASQUERADE was the missing piece for the return path.


9. rp_filter — the silent killer

What is rp_filter: Reverse path filter — a kernel security check. For every incoming packet, the kernel asks: "if I had to reply to this source IP, would I send it back out this same interface?" If the answer is no, the packet is silently dropped. No log, no error, no counter — nothing. That's what makes it dangerous to troubleshoot.

After steps 7 and 8, VLAN 1794 worked. VLANs 1797 and 1798 still timed out.

Why I checked this: Same fixes applied to all VLANs, same setup, but 1794 worked and 1797/1798 didn't. My RAW-PRE tag fired on those VLANs (packets arriving) but nothing after — packet was getting dropped between raw and nat. Not many things sit between raw PREROUTING and nat PREROUTING. Connection tracking and rp_filter are the main suspects. Conntrack was fine (working for 1794), so rp_filter was next.

Check rp_filter:
oc debug node/ocp-ai-master01.calix.local -- chroot /host sysctl -a | grep "rp_filter" | grep bnd0

What I found: All bnd0.* interfaces had rp_filter=1 (strict mode). External clients from 10.172.248.x were hitting VIPs on bnd0.1797 and bnd0.1798. The kernel checked: "would I route a reply to 10.172.248.x via bnd0.1797?" — no, that subnet isn't on VLAN 1797. Packet dropped.

Fix:
sysctl -w net.ipv4.conf.all.rp_filter=0
sysctl -w net.ipv4.conf.default.rp_filter=0
sysctl -w net.ipv4.conf.bnd0/1794.rp_filter=0
sysctl -w net.ipv4.conf.bnd0/1797.rp_filter=0
sysctl -w net.ipv4.conf.bnd0/1798.rp_filter=0

Note: sysctl uses / instead of . for interface names (bnd0/1794 not bnd0.1794).

After disabling rp_filter on all bnd0.* interfaces on all nodes, VLANs 1797 and 1798 immediately started working.

Why 1794 worked but 1797/1798 didn't: I'm not 100% certain on this — it may have been related to how the routing tables were set up differently for that subnet, or it may have been that I tested 1794 cross-node (where source IP was on the same VLAN subnet) vs externally (where source IP was on a different VLAN). Either way, rp_filter=1 was the cause for 1797/1798 and disabling it fixed them immediately.


10. Validation — all 8 VIPs

for ip_port in 10.172.194.160:9000 10.172.194.161:19530 10.172.194.163:5432 \
               10.172.198.160:9000 10.172.198.161:19530 \
               10.172.202.160:9000 10.172.202.161:19530 10.172.202.163:5432; do
  echo -n "Testing $ip_port: "
  nc -zv ${ip_port%:*} ${ip_port#*:} 2>&1 | tail -1
done

All 8 returned "succeeded" after the rp_filter fix.


11. Making it permanent — MachineConfig

All the fixes above are lost on reboot. Created two MachineConfigs (master + worker) with:
- /etc/sysctl.d/99-metallb-rp-filter.conf — disables rp_filter on bnd0.* interfaces
- /etc/NetworkManager/dispatcher.d/99-metallb-vlan-routing — runs on bnd0.* interface up, sets rp_filter=0 and adds ClusterIP route to the right policy table
- /usr/local/bin/metallb-vlan-routing-setup.sh — systemd oneshot at boot, adds MASQUERADE rule, sets rp_filter, adds ClusterIP routes to tables 100/101/102
- metallb-vlan-routing.service — runs the setup script after OVS and NetworkManager are up

MachineConfigs pushed to ArgoCD repo: 99-metallb-vlan-routing-master and 99-metallb-vlan-routing-worker.

Important MachineConfig gotchas I hit:
- Must use Ignition 3.5.0 (not 3.2.0 — wrong version causes RenderDegraded which blocks ALL MC updates)
- File modes must be decimal (493 = 0755, 420 = 0644)
- File contents must be base64 data URI, not inline


CNPG Recovery

During the MachineConfig rollout, MCO drained master01. CNPG tried switching the PostgreSQL primary from db-1 (on master01) to db-2. The switchover got stuck.

What happened:
- db-1 pod got evicted from master01
- db-2 couldn't promote — stuck replaying WAL from the MinIO archive
- WAL files in MinIO had system identifier 7621790087615889432
- db-2's pg_control had system identifier 7623307342724771863
- Mismatch = WAL from a previous/different cluster instance
- db-2 kept looping: restore WAL from MinIO -> mismatch -> try streaming replication -> connection refused -> wait -> repeat

How to check:
oc logs pai-apps-db-2 -n pai-prod --tail=100 | grep -iE "wal|system identifier|recover|promot"

What I actually saw in the logs (repeating every ~5 seconds):
  {"msg":"Restored WAL file","walName":"000000010000000000000035","elapsedWalTime":0.309}
  {"message":"restored log file \"000000010000000000000035\" from archive"}
  {"message":"WAL file is from different database system: WAL file database system identifier is 7621790087615889432, pg_control database system identifier is 7623307342724771863"}
  {"message":"could not connect to the primary server: connection to server at \"pai-apps-db-rw\" (172.30.138.226), port 5432 failed: Connection refused"}
  {"message":"waiting for WAL to become available at 0/35000078"}

The key line: "WAL file is from different database system" — the WAL archive in MinIO was from a different PostgreSQL instance than what's running.

What cnpg status showed when stuck:
kubectl cnpg status pai-apps-db -n pai-prod

  Name           Current LSN  Replication role  Status         Node
  pai-apps-db-1  -            -                 InternalError  ocp-ai-master01.calix.local
  pai-apps-db-2  -            -                 InternalError  ocp-ai-master02.calix.local
  pai-apps-db-3  -            -                 InternalError  ocp-ai-master03.calix.local

All InternalError with no LSN = no primary is up.

I also checked what CNPG was injecting into PostgreSQL config:
oc exec pai-apps-db-2 -n pai-prod -c postgres -- cat /var/lib/postgresql/data/pgdata/override.conf

What I saw:
  primary_conninfo = 'host=pai-apps-db-rw user=streaming_replica port=5432 ...'
  primary_slot_name = '_cnpg_pai_apps_db_2'
  recovery_target_timeline = 'latest'
  restore_command = '/controller/manager wal-restore --log-destination /controller/log/postgres.json %f %p'

The restore_command is what pulls WAL from MinIO. primary_conninfo points to pai-apps-db-rw (which is itself, but can't connect because it hasn't started). That's why the instance loops — it keeps trying to restore bad WAL and connect to a primary that doesn't exist.

Recovery steps (in order of what I tried):
1. Patched cluster status to set db-2 as primary:
   oc patch cluster pai-apps-db -n pai-prod --type merge --subresource status -p '{"status":{"currentPrimary":"pai-apps-db-2","targetPrimary":"pai-apps-db-2"}}'
   Result: Cluster phase changed but db-2 still stuck in the recovery loop.

2. Tried pg_ctl promote:
   oc exec pai-apps-db-2 -n pai-prod -c postgres -- pg_ctl promote -D /var/lib/postgresql/data/pgdata
   Result: "cannot promote server; server is not in standby mode" — PostgreSQL thought it was already primary but was stuck in crash recovery replaying bad WAL.

3. Removed standby.signal:
   oc exec pai-apps-db-2 -n pai-prod -c postgres -- rm /var/lib/postgresql/data/pgdata/standby.signal
   Result: Didn't help — the restore_command in override.conf was still pulling bad WAL from MinIO.

4. Cleared override.conf:
   oc exec pai-apps-db-2 -n pai-prod -c postgres -- sh -c 'echo "" > /var/lib/postgresql/data/pgdata/override.conf'
   Then restarted postgres:
   oc exec pai-apps-db-2 -n pai-prod -c postgres -- pg_ctl restart -D /var/lib/postgresql/data/pgdata -m fast
   Result: Container got killed (exit 137). CNPG operator rewrote override.conf on restart — back to square one.

5. Renamed the bad WAL archive in MinIO so restore_command can't find anything:
   oc exec minio-85b4477cdc-t275f -n pai-prod -- mv /data/cnpg-backups/pai-prod/pai-apps-db/wals /data/cnpg-backups/pai-prod/pai-apps-db/wals.bak
   Result: WAL directory gone, but PostgreSQL still stuck — it needed WAL file 000000010000000000000035 for crash recovery and couldn't find it anywhere now.

6. Forced WAL reset with pg_resetwal (had to catch the container while it was crashlooping):
   while ! oc exec pai-apps-db-2 -n pai-prod -c postgres -- pg_resetwal -f /var/lib/postgresql/data/pgdata 2>/dev/null; do echo "waiting..."; sleep 2; done
   Result: "Write-ahead log reset" — db-2 came up as primary. db-1 reconnected as standby automatically.

7. db-3 was also stuck. Tried pg_ctl stop then pg_resetwal but the container died between the two commands. Ended up deleting the PVC and pod:
   oc delete pvc/pai-apps-db-3 pod/pai-apps-db-3 -n pai-prod
   Result: CNPG rebuilt it as db-4 via pg_basebackup from db-2. Came up clean.

Final cnpg status after recovery:
  Name           Current LSN  Replication role      Status  Node
  pai-apps-db-2  0/3A026238   Primary               OK      ocp-ai-master02.calix.local
  pai-apps-db-1  0/3A026238   Standby (file based)  OK      ocp-ai-master01.calix.local
  pai-apps-db-4  0/3A026238   Standby (file based)  OK      ocp-ai-master03.calix.local

Key commands for CNPG troubleshooting:
kubectl cnpg status pai-apps-db -n pai-prod
kubectl cnpg hibernate on pai-apps-db -n pai-prod
kubectl cnpg hibernate off pai-apps-db -n pai-prod
kubectl cnpg promote pai-apps-db <instance> -n pai-prod


Summary of changes applied

OVN-Kubernetes network config (cluster-level, persistent):
1. ipForwarding: Global — allows IP forwarding across OVN-managed interfaces for external traffic
2. routingViaHost: true — routes traffic through the host kernel stack so it can reach OVN from secondary interfaces

MetalLB routing fixes (applied to all 3 master nodes):
1. Added ClusterIP route (172.30.0.0/16 via 169.254.0.4 dev br-ex) to policy routing tables 100, 101, 102 — so DNAT'd packets go into OVN instead of out the VLAN gateway
2. Added MASQUERADE rule in nat POSTROUTING for DNAT'd traffic going to br-ex — so OVN can route the reply back
3. Disabled rp_filter (set to 0) on all bnd0.* VLAN interfaces — so the kernel stops silently dropping packets from external subnets

Made permanent via MachineConfig:
- 99-metallb-vlan-routing-master (applied to master MCP)
- 99-metallb-vlan-routing-worker (applied to worker MCP)
- Both pushed to ArgoCD repo

CNPG recovery actions:
1. Ran pg_resetwal -f on db-2 to clear the WAL mismatch and force it up as primary
2. Deleted PVC and pod for db-3 — CNPG rebuilt it as db-4 via pg_basebackup
3. Renamed wals to wals.bak in MinIO to prevent restore_command from pulling bad WAL


